DOC DEL- Sorry, I've been south of the border and away from the computer.  I don't think I ever said, in reference to what happened to returning vets, &quot;none of these things happened.&quot;  I just stated that I didn't think the spitters were in the majority (and were a small minority). And, sorry, but I don't think there's much you can say to sway me from my opinion, which is based on not only my experiences, but on what vets have shared with me.  Of course, I am reading what you and others have posted here.<br>
ON IVORY TOWERS- Uh, I wouldn't describe my present place of employment as an Ivory Tower.  If you only knew....<br>
ON DOC SPATZ SOMETIMES &quot;LOSING IT&quot;- I understand that in your field, like teaching high school, stress can be a serious problem, and perhaps venting online from time to time is a way to relieve it.  You feel better.  Doc, in addition to teaching 4 classes (in 4 different rooms) I coordinate and run various support groups for our young people- grief, pregnancy, children of divorce, alcohol &amp; drug, children of alcoholics/drug abusers, kids in crisis, gay/lesbian, stress, tobacco cessation, etc.  During the Gulf War a number of our kids had brothers or friends serving, they were scared, we formed a support group for them.  We run from 10-17 groups a week for our kids.  I have a very stressful job.  If I told my wife one-tenth of the stories I hear, I think she'd leave me just so she wouldn't have to listen to that stuff every night.  Now, to relieve the stress, I could go home and (a) slap my wife around, (b) beat my kids, (c) kick the dog a few times or (d) vent all over your ass online.  I choose to do neither.  I keep it all inside.  Hence, 2 heart attacks.  Lately, I have gone out of my way to be civil to you, resisting my baser instincts (mainly because I think you actually *try* to provoke us sometimes).  You respond by dumping all over me. What lesson can be learned from this?<br>
TO ALL- Sorry this post digresses from the current thread. I'll lurk for awhile, pick up on what's going on, and, perhaps, join in.<br>
Happy Ides of March!  Et tu, Doc Spatz?
